didn't take her long to feel
like she also had to give back,

00:35:24.300 --> 00:35:26.100
just two years in.

00:35:26.100 --> 00:35:30.390
So there were some
amazing folks that night.

00:35:30.390 --> 00:35:34.730
It was sort of the cap-off
to social media week.

00:35:34.730 --> 00:35:40.940
But it just showed
how much support

00:35:40.940 --> 00:35:44.610
there is to provide more
opportunities to more

00:35:44.610 --> 00:35:47.450
people and all of the
great organizations

00:35:47.450 --> 00:35:50.260
that are in New York that
are out there to help.

00:35:52.812 --> 00:35:55.020
HEATHER THOMPSON RIVERA: So
how are we doing on time?

00:35:55.020 --> 00:35:57.820
I think we may want to start
to wrap up so that we can

00:35:57.820 --> 00:35:59.220
save some time for questions.

00:35:59.220 --> 00:36:03.340
So maybe I'll close on
something forward-looking.

00:36:03.340 --> 00:36:07.610
I'd love to know what is your
vision for the New York City

00:36:07.610 --> 00:36:10.270
tech community in the
next five to 10 years?

00:36:10.270 --> 00:36:12.970
And then, when you even think
beyond the next five to 10

00:36:12.970 --> 00:36:15.140
years and you're
thinking about, what's

00:36:15.140 --> 00:36:19.270
the person who's sitting in your
job, say 15, 20 years from now,

00:36:19.270 --> 00:36:20.880
what do you hope
are the problems

00:36:20.880 --> 00:36:23.584
or challenges that they'll
be solving at that point?

00:36:23.584 --> 00:36:24.500
MINERVA TANTOCO: Yeah.

00:36:24.500 --> 00:36:29.440
I think we're seeing some of
the seeds of this amazing future

00:36:29.440 --> 00:36:30.882
of New York City already.

00:36:30.882 --> 00:36:32.340
One of the biggest
trends, I think,

00:36:32.340 --> 00:36:34.460
is the notion of
social innovation,

00:36:34.460 --> 00:36:36.650
that is, tech for good.

00:36:36.650 --> 00:36:39.570
Because being a woman in
tech and being a coder

00:36:39.570 --> 00:36:41.560
is a superpower.

00:36:41.560 --> 00:36:44.690
And we need to use our
superpowers for good.

00:36:44.690 --> 00:36:48.440
How can we use technology to
help the poorest among us,

00:36:48.440 --> 00:36:52.120
the immigrants, the
people that have no voice?

00:36:52.120 --> 00:36:55.770
And one of the
privileges of my role

00:36:55.770 --> 00:36:58.800
is I get to see all the people
that are making that happen.

00:36:58.800 --> 00:37:07.736
And so, yes, it's OK to use
tech to sell a few more pencils

00:37:07.736 --> 00:37:10.360
or, do you want some socks
to go with those pencils?

00:37:10.360 --> 00:37:13.010
Whatever it is.

00:37:13.010 --> 00:37:17.200
But to be able to use
those kinds of technologies

00:37:17.200 --> 00:37:19.810
to really deliver government
services where they can

00:37:19.810 --> 00:37:24.520
do the most good, to
come up with new wireless

00:37:24.520 --> 00:37:26.740
technologies that
will expand broadband

00:37:26.740 --> 00:37:32.070
to the digital deserts,
that is really taking hold.

00:37:32.070 --> 00:37:34.010
And I think New
York City really is

00:37:34.010 --> 00:37:37.050
the epicenter of a
lot of that activity

00:37:37.050 --> 00:37:41.210
because it's an ecosystem
of social do-gooder techies

00:37:41.210 --> 00:37:44.830
that are all meeting and
percolating together.

00:37:44.830 --> 00:37:47.290
When we think about the
city streets and the idea

00:37:47.290 --> 00:37:52.150
of a connected city, again,
I see a huge opportunity,

00:37:52.150 --> 00:37:55.600
where right now we have a lot
of the personal technology.

00:37:55.600 --> 00:37:59.560
And sometimes, that has the
effect of actually alienating

00:37:59.560 --> 00:38:01.200
us from each other.

00:38:01.200 --> 00:38:03.040
We're there, but
we're not there.

00:38:03.040 --> 00:38:05.190
You know, that photo
of everyone at dinner,

00:38:05.190 --> 00:38:06.890
but they're all
looking at their phone.

00:38:06.890 --> 00:38:09.440
Like, are they at
dinner together, really?

00:38:09.440 --> 00:38:12.980
Or are they just sitting within
a few feet of each other,

00:38:12.980 --> 00:38:15.040
but doing something
someplace else?

00:38:15.040 --> 00:38:15.820
HEATHER THOMPSON
RIVERA: I saw a couple

00:38:15.820 --> 00:38:18.111
on a date the other night
that was very much like that.

00:38:18.111 --> 00:38:20.220
I was like, I'm pretty
sure they're on a date.

00:38:20.220 --> 00:38:22.157
Neither of them was
talking to each other,

00:38:22.157 --> 00:38:24.490
and they were both looking
at their phones for, like, 30

00:38:24.490 --> 00:38:26.440
minutes while we were
just kind of passing by.

00:38:26.440 --> 00:38:29.751
So I completely understand
that concept of alienation.

00:38:29.751 --> 00:38:31.250
MINERVA TANTOCO:
And I think that we

00:38:31.250 --> 00:38:33.770
can have a notion
of technology that

00:38:33.770 --> 00:38:35.660
actually connects us better.

00:38:35.660 --> 00:38:38.780
And there's no better place
than in sort of public spaces.

00:38:38.780 --> 00:38:42.300
So yes, we're going to have
the self-driving cars that you

00:38:42.300 --> 00:38:45.050
can call up with your phone.

00:38:45.050 --> 00:38:47.400
That's all going to
happen, for sure.

00:38:47.400 --> 00:38:49.770
But also, I think we
have an opportunity

00:38:49.770 --> 00:38:54.710
to say, how can we connect
the virtual and physical

00:38:54.710 --> 00:38:57.840
communities to
connect to each other?

00:38:57.840 --> 00:39:00.010
And how do we make
our streets safer?

00:39:00.010 --> 00:39:05.284
How do we use technology
to band together?

00:39:05.284 --> 00:39:07.980
I've seen a lot of apps
that are like, well,

00:39:07.980 --> 00:39:10.380
who are the homebound
folks in your building?

00:39:10.380 --> 00:39:13.930
And maybe you could bring
them food once in a while.

00:39:13.930 --> 00:39:20.380
Or in an emergency, how we get
together and help our neighbors

00:39:20.380 --> 00:39:22.570
who might be flooded out.

00:39:22.570 --> 00:39:25.530
And so I think we
have a real, not just

00:39:25.530 --> 00:39:27.360
an opportunity but
a responsibility,

00:39:27.360 --> 00:39:30.590
as folks who have
this superpower,

00:39:30.590 --> 00:39:33.960
to really figure out the
vision of New York City

00:39:33.960 --> 00:39:38.240
as a smart and equitable
city, a city whose heart

00:39:38.240 --> 00:39:40.292
is as big as our brains.

00:39:40.292 --> 00:39:42.750
HEATHER THOMPSON RIVERA: That's
an amazing picture and kind

00:39:42.750 --> 00:39:45.420
of painting in your head to
go off into the world with.

00:39:45.420 --> 00:39:48.480
So I know I for one am
very excited to continue

00:39:48.480 --> 00:39:51.940
to work here and be able to
experience life in New York

00:39:51.940 --> 00:39:53.096
and work in New York.

00:39:53.096 --> 00:39:54.720
And I'm really
appreciative that you've

00:39:54.720 --> 00:39:57.311
given me some time to get to
know you a little bit better.

00:39:57.311 --> 00:39:59.560
And I feel like since I've
had the privilege of asking

00:39:59.560 --> 00:40:01.560
all the questions, maybe
I should turn it over

00:40:01.560 --> 00:40:02.300
to you guys.

