here came to obviously
meet new folks

00:40:24.670 --> 00:40:26.670
and hopefully collaborate
on different projects?

00:40:26.670 --> 00:40:28.530
Just by a show of hands.

00:40:28.530 --> 00:40:31.070
We know you've got
full-time jobs.

00:40:31.070 --> 00:40:31.720
OK, cool.

00:40:31.720 --> 00:40:32.220
Awesome.

00:40:32.220 --> 00:40:35.160
And Minerva, can you talk
about artificial intelligence

00:40:35.160 --> 00:40:38.250
and some of the use cases for
some of the top companies?

00:40:38.250 --> 00:40:40.350
What are they doing with
artificial intelligence,

00:40:40.350 --> 00:40:41.860
now and in the next five years?

00:40:41.860 --> 00:40:42.437
Thanks.

00:40:42.437 --> 00:40:43.520
MINERVA TANTOCO: Oh, cool.

00:40:43.520 --> 00:40:47.120
I love the geeky questions.

00:40:47.120 --> 00:40:47.935
Thank you for that.

00:40:47.935 --> 00:40:48.435
Oh!

00:40:48.435 --> 00:40:50.850
I love geeking out.

00:40:50.850 --> 00:40:57.124
So when I started 30 years ago,
the biggest change between then

00:40:57.124 --> 00:40:58.790
and now-- and people
ask, why didn't you

00:40:58.790 --> 00:41:01.755
continue with your AI after
you sold your first company?

00:41:01.755 --> 00:41:05.330
And the truth is that
between 1990 and 2000,

00:41:05.330 --> 00:41:07.170
it's called the AI winter.

00:41:07.170 --> 00:41:08.660
Everybody was
really disappointed

00:41:08.660 --> 00:41:12.310
that AI didn't deliver
what it promised.

00:41:12.310 --> 00:41:14.560
And all of the
venture capital for AI

00:41:14.560 --> 00:41:16.530
dried up during that decade.

00:41:16.530 --> 00:41:18.320
So I found other
stuff to do, clearly.

00:41:18.320 --> 00:41:23.870
But now, we have an even
more powerful opportunity

00:41:23.870 --> 00:41:26.830
with artificial
intelligence because we

00:41:26.830 --> 00:41:28.090
have three main factors.

00:41:28.090 --> 00:41:32.390
One, we have massive compute
now because of the way

00:41:32.390 --> 00:41:33.060
that we can do.

00:41:33.060 --> 00:41:35.000
We were working on--
this well before even

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:36.540
the 286 was invented.

00:41:36.540 --> 00:41:40.670
So I won't bore you, but we
had to basically turn a crank

00:41:40.670 --> 00:41:43.340
to make the computer go.

00:41:43.340 --> 00:41:49.480
And secondly, we have
massive data because before,

00:41:49.480 --> 00:41:52.030
we couldn't compute
all that data.

00:41:52.030 --> 00:41:55.120
And now we've got
massive data from which

00:41:55.120 --> 00:41:57.920
to apply the deep learning to.

00:41:57.920 --> 00:41:59.770
And the third big
component, of course,

00:41:59.770 --> 00:42:01.200
is the massive connectivity.

00:42:01.200 --> 00:42:03.700
So 30 years ago, it
was pre-internet.

00:42:03.700 --> 00:42:07.500
And those three things
are the magic sauce

00:42:07.500 --> 00:42:11.830
that's now why AI and just
sort of intelligence systems

00:42:11.830 --> 00:42:18.280
generally is finally
coming into its own.

00:42:18.280 --> 00:42:20.990
And so what I see
is a future not

00:42:20.990 --> 00:42:23.390
of replacing human
intelligence, which

00:42:23.390 --> 00:42:26.230
is what artificial
intelligence means sometimes.

00:42:26.230 --> 00:42:30.340
I think of AI now as an
intelligent assistance.

00:42:30.340 --> 00:42:32.780
It's going to allow
us to really process

00:42:32.780 --> 00:42:35.720
all the crazy amounts of
data because now, we're

00:42:35.720 --> 00:42:39.870
spewing terabytes of
data every few minutes--

00:42:39.870 --> 00:42:43.470
my watch, the phones,
everybody's phone

00:42:43.470 --> 00:42:46.310
is spewing out all kinds
of data and information.

00:42:46.310 --> 00:42:49.800
So I think we can use
intelligent assistance

00:42:49.800 --> 00:42:54.330
to help us make humans
smarter instead of trying

00:42:54.330 --> 00:42:56.844
to replace what humans do.

00:42:56.844 --> 00:42:57.510
AUDIENCE: Great.

00:42:57.510 --> 00:42:58.110
Thank you.

00:42:58.110 --> 00:42:59.450
HEATHER THOMPSON
RIVERA: Thank you.

00:42:59.450 --> 00:42:59.770
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:42:59.770 --> 00:43:00.390
My name's Kelby.

00:43:00.390 --> 00:43:01.806
I'm from Florida
State University.

00:43:01.806 --> 00:43:03.370
I'm a sophomore.

00:43:03.370 --> 00:43:05.561
Just a quick question
regarding women in tech--

00:43:05.561 --> 00:43:07.810
so there's something that
you said that kind of really

00:43:07.810 --> 00:43:08.650
spoke to me.

00:43:08.650 --> 00:43:13.030
And recently, I went into an
interview with a tech company,

00:43:13.030 --> 00:43:16.040
and the interviewer
was like, well, yeah.

00:43:16.040 --> 00:43:16.790
You're a woman.

00:43:16.790 --> 00:43:18.540
That's part of the
reason why you're here.

00:43:18.540 --> 00:43:20.274
And I was like, hmm.

00:43:20.274 --> 00:43:21.190
He's like, no, no, no.

00:43:21.190 --> 00:43:25.060
You're qualified, but-- and
every time somebody says "but,"

00:43:25.060 --> 00:43:27.960
they don't mean what
they said at first.

00:43:27.960 --> 00:43:30.980
And it is a common theme here
to get more women in tech.

00:43:30.980 --> 00:43:33.000
And you want to see
more women in tech.

00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:36.410
However, do you feel that
there will come a day whenever

00:43:36.410 --> 00:43:40.000
there's too many women, and men
suddenly become the minority?

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:44.710
And how do we stop that because
one thing that's very important

00:43:44.710 --> 00:43:47.820
is that women are
underrepresented in the tech

00:43:47.820 --> 00:43:48.320
field.

00:43:48.320 --> 00:43:50.220
And everything
that's being created

00:43:50.220 --> 00:43:52.630
is all by a male's mentality.

00:43:52.630 --> 00:43:55.050
So by getting women in and
being able to collaborate,

00:43:55.050 --> 00:43:55.960
we have both sides.

00:43:55.960 --> 00:43:59.010
But do you think there
will ever be a day where

00:43:59.010 --> 00:44:00.080
women become too much?

00:44:00.080 --> 00:44:02.230
And how do we stop
that from happening?

00:44:02.230 --> 00:44:03.785
How do we get to
the perfect 50/50?

00:44:06.887 --> 00:44:08.970
MINERVA TANTOCO: It's such
an interesting question

00:44:08.970 --> 00:44:15.580
because I don't know if the idea
is to be this perfect 50-50.

00:44:15.580 --> 00:44:22.630
What I look at as my parents and
grandparents grew up in a time

00:44:22.630 --> 00:44:26.820
where being a woman doctor
or being a woman lawyer

00:44:26.820 --> 00:44:29.320
was a big deal.

00:44:29.320 --> 00:44:34.400
I look forward to the time
when it's just not a big deal.

00:44:34.400 --> 00:44:39.930
That it's just like, yeah, woman
doctor and woman technologist.

00:44:39.930 --> 00:44:45.170
So whether that's a percentage,
it's much more cultural,

00:44:45.170 --> 00:44:50.610
this idea that-- I think
we're right to bring attention

00:44:50.610 --> 00:44:53.810
to it now because
it's clearly an issue,

00:44:53.810 --> 00:44:59.920
economic and fairness,
for both those reasons.

00:44:59.920 --> 00:45:05.420
But also, my dream is
that, yeah, you're a baker.

00:45:05.420 --> 00:45:07.320
You're a mom.

00:45:07.320 --> 00:45:09.687
You're a crossfitter.

00:45:09.687 --> 00:45:14.120
Oh, and you're an AI scientist.

00:45:14.120 --> 00:45:17.600
And so that's my vision
of where things can go.

00:45:17.600 --> 00:45:26.744
And I hope that events like
this sort of make it OK.

00:45:26.744 --> 00:45:27.910
AUDIENCE: Thank you so much.

